{"key":"post-10713945","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10713945</id>\n<content>Minimum 4 hours, maximum 24.&amp;nbsp;  I used to soak up to 48 hours sometimes but found a higher bacterial contamination rate from long soaks.&amp;nbsp; Many endospores germinate and form new endospores within a few hours, so long soaks are actually counter-productive.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I have a very busy schedule, so don't have time to sit and time the soaks.&amp;nbsp; I usually rinse and begin the soak in the morning, and then PC in the evening of the same day.&amp;nbsp; Often, I'll do the reverse, beginning the soak at bedtime, and PCing in the morning.&amp;nbsp; If I need to run several batches(I have five PCs), I'll go the minimum soak time in order to turn out product faster.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10714208</next>\n<prev>10713653</prev>\n<first>10704658</first>\n<last>10714353</last>\n<when>1248188761</when>\n<utime>07/21/09 06:06 PM</utime>\n</post>"}